"Jouzel J., Lorius C.","Climate evolution: From the recent past to the future [Evolution du climat: Du passe recent vers le futur]",1999,"Comptes Rendus de l'Academie de Sciences - Serie IIa: Sciences de la Terre et des Planetes","328","4",,"229","239",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033058248&partnerID=40&md5=b7246316c97a4e669959770fa2b2d930","Lab. Sci. Climat l'Environnement, L'Orme des Merisiers, CEA Saclay, 91191 Gif-sur-Yvette Cedex, France; Lab. Glaciologie Geophysique l'E., CNRS, BP96, 38402, Saint-Martin-d'Heres Cedex, France","Jouzel, J., Lab. Sci. Climat l'Environnement, L'Orme des Merisiers, CEA Saclay, 91191 Gif-sur-Yvette Cedex, France; Lorius, C., Lab. Glaciologie Geophysique l'E., CNRS, BP96, 38402, Saint-Martin-d'Heres Cedex, France","The aim of this article is twofold. We first summarize our current scientific knowledge about the potential influence of human activities on climate. This review is largely based on the conclusions of the 1995 IPCC report (International Panel on Climate Change). An increase in atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases has been observed since 1750 (CH4 = 145%; CO2 = 30%; N2O = 15%) and in the temperature of the Earth's surface since 1860 (between 0.3 and 0.6°C). This report suggests a discernable human influence on climate and predicts significant global warming for the next century (1 to 3.5 °C) as a result of the anthropogenic increase of the greenhouse effect. We then show how studies of past climates have, over the last ten years, contributed to this problem by providing information relevant to the future of our climate. Important results concern the existence of a relationship between climate and concentrations of greenhouse gases for more than 200 000 years, the discovery of rapid climatic changes (~10°C in a few decades in Greenland) and the reconstruction of recent climate showing that the 20th century is the warmest since 1 400 AD.","GIEC/IPCC; Greenhouse warming; Palaeoclimates","climate change; greenhouse effect; paleoclimate",,,,,,"Bender, M., Sowers, T., Dickson, M.L., Orchado, J., Grootes, P., Mayewski, P.A., Meese, D.A., Climate connection between Greenland and Antarctica during the last 100 000 yr (1994) Nature, 372, pp. 663-666; Blunier, T., Chappellaz, J., Scwhander, J., Barnola, J.-M., Desperts, T., Stauffer, B., Raynaud, D., Atmospheric methane record from a Greenland ice core over the last 1 000 yr (1993) Geophys. Res. Lett., 20, pp. 2219-2222; Blunier, T., Chappellaz, J., Schwander, J., Dallenbäch, A., Stauffer, B., Stocker, T., Raynaud, D., Johnsen, S.J., Asynchrony of Greenland and Antarctic climate during the last glacial period (1998) Nature, 394, pp. 739-743; Bond, G., Broecker, W.S., Johnsen, S.J., Mc Manus, J., Labeyrie, L.D., Jouzel, J., Bonani, G., Correlations between climate records from North Atlantic sediments and Greenland ice (1993) Nature, 365, pp. 143-147; Bradley, R.S., Jones, P.D., Little Ice Age summer temperature variations : Their nature and relevance to recent global warming trends (1993) The Holocene, 3, pp. 367-376; Chappellaz, J., Blunier, T., Raynaud, D., Barnola, J.-M., Schwander, J., Stauffer, B., Synchronous changes in atmospheric CH4 and Greenland climate between 40 and 8 kyr BP (1993) Nature, 366, pp. 443-445; Chappellaz, J., Brook, E., Blunier, T., Malaizé, B., CH4 and δ18O of O2 records from Greenland ice : A clue for stratigraphic disturbance in the bottom part of the GRIP and GISP2 ice-cores (1997) J. Geophys. Res., 102, pp. 26547-26557; (1997) A Research Programme on Climate Variability and Prediction for the 21st Century, 48p. , World Climate Research Programme; Dansgaard, W., Clausen, H.B., Gundestrup, N., Hammer, C.U., Johnsen, S.J., Krinstindottir, P., Reeh, N., A new Greenland deep ice core (1982) Science, 218, pp. 1273-1277; Dansgaard, W., Johnsen, S.J., Clausen, H.B., Dahl-Jensen, D., Gunderstrup, N.S., Hammer, C.U., Steffensen, J.P., Bond, G., Evidence for general instability of past cli